iraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht, Ahvaz)\n\nThe key question: Does this evidence meet the standard of \"preponderance of the evidence\" that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET?\n\nLet's evaluate the rule requirements:\n- Iran initiated the closure: Evidence consistently shows Iranian Civil Aviation Authority (CAA)/Civil Aviation Organization as the issuing authority\n- Not solely weather-related: All reports indicate security/military context (US missile threats, etc.), no weather references\n- By May 24 deadline: NOTAM effective May 22 20:46Z to May 25 08:30Z - May 25 08:30Z is after 11:59 PM ET on May 24? Need to convert timezones.\n\nWait - we need to know if the closure was active at the deadline. May 25 08:30Z is 01:30 AM ET on May 25 (since Z is UTC, ET is UTC-5, so UTC 08:30 is ET 03:30). But May 24 11:59 PM ET is equivalent to May 25 04:59 UTC (which is less than 08:30 UTC), so the closure was active through the deadline.\n\n- \"Major closure\" definition: The rule has two paths:\n  1. Broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region\n  2. Complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports\n\nFor path 1: Western Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region? Yes, the rule defines this specifically - western airspace closure was mentioned as a qualifying example in PX-0.\n\nFor path 2: The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals/departures at two listed airports. According to the evidence:\n- PX-1 says \"only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas\"\n- DX-1 says \"several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset\"\n\nFor