e wants the official NOTAM document, but the rule doesn't explicitly say the official document is required - it says \"primary resolution sources\" which can include \"a consensus of credible reporting.\"\n\nLooking at the evidence consistency:\n- All three plaintiff exhibits (PX-1, PX-2, PX-3) identify OIIX A1010/26 NOTAM for western Tehran FIR closure from May 22-25\n- All three mention the limited daylight operations with new approvals needed\n- PX-2 provides precise UTC timing, confirming the closure was in effect through May 24 deadline\n- DX-1 confirms the CAO/CAA has acknowledged a western FIR suspension with limited operations\n\nThe only discrepancy is whether there was a \"new\" notice - DX-1 says there wasn't a new notice, but PX-1-3 discuss the NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, which may have been issued before the denial statement, so there may not be a contradiction.\n\nBased on this, I believe the preponderance of evidence does show that Iran initiated a major closure meeting the market rule's definition. The plaintiff has identified multiple consistent secondary reports that converge on the same core facts, and even the defense's evidence (DX-1) partially corroborates the closure's existence while disputing the \"new\" nature of the notice.\n\nThe evidence shows:\n- Iran's civil aviation authority issued instructions for western Tehran FIR closure\n- It was effective before the deadline (May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET)\n- It was not weather-related (security context)\n- Western Tehran FIR qualifies as a major Iranian airspace region under the market rule\n- The rule specifically states that limited exceptions don't disqualify such a closure\n\nTherefore, the proposition should be \"demonstrated.\"\n\nBut let's be precise about what \"demonstrated\" means - it means the evidence shows the proposition is more likely true than not. There are reasonable doubts, but based on the consistent evidence from multiple sources and even the defense's own admission of some closure, I believe the preponderance standard is met.\n\nI should make sure I use the exact tool call format: `mcp` with tool `aar_submit_council_vote` and arguments as JSON string.\n\nThe rationale needs to be very brief - no more than 3 sentences.\n\nLet me draft a rationale:\n\"The admitted evidence from multiple credible sources consistently shows Iran's civil aviation authority imposed a western Tehran FIR closure with limited exceptions, effective before the deadline, for security reasons. The record confirms this qualifies as a major closure of a major Iranian airspace region under the rule, which permits limited exceptions. The preponderance of evidence supports the proposition.\"","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_a0f146d433d54ca58e91a1","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Multiple consistent secondary reports confirm an Iranian civil aviation authority-imposed western Tehran FIR closure before the deadline for security reasons. The western FIR qualifies as a major airspace region under the rule, which allows limited exceptions. The"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"Multiple consistent secondary reports confirm an Iranian civil aviation authority-imposed western Tehran FIR closure before the deadline for security reasons. The western FIR qualifies as a major airspace region under the rule, which allows limited exceptions. The","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782834277031,"responseId":"gen-1782834277-uVQ9NIdIVG2CR2W3aYTH","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to analyze the case thoroughly. Let's process this step by step.\n\nFirst, let's review what we have from the `mcp` call to `aar_wait_for_opportunity`. I received `state: ready` with opportunity details. The prompt provides the core case information:\n\nProposition: \"By May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET, Iran initiated a major non-weather closure of its airspace within the meaning of the market rule.\"\n\nThe record shows:\n\nEvidence:\nPlaintiff's exhibits:\n- PX-0 (Market rule): Defines what qualifies as a \"major closure\" - broad closure of commercial flights across Iranian airspace/major Iranian airspace region or complete suspension of commercial arrivals/departures affecting at least two listed airports (IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, IFN)\n- PX-1 (Indian Express): Reports Iran closed western airspace from May 22-25 with NOTAM OIIX A1010/26; only 8 airports operational with daylight restrictions; requires fresh CAA approval\n- PX-2 (Kenya Times): Provides detailed NOTAM timing: May 22 20:46Z to May 25 08:30Z; western Tehran FIR closed except daylight operations; prior permissions suspended, new approvals needed for IFR passenger operations\n- PX-3 (Siasat): Confirms NOTAM OIIX A1010/26 for western Tehran FIR; limited daylight operations; fresh CAA approval needed for passenger flights\n- PX-R2 (Kenya Times again): Additional details on specific airport codes affected (OITR, OIKK, OIAA, OISS, OIYY, OICC, OIGG, OIAW)\n- PX-R3 (Market rule again): Repeats the rule definition\n\nDefendant's evidence:\n- DX-1 (Iran International): Reports CAO denied issuing a \"new official aviation notice\" imposing restrictions, but also acknowledges that earlier CAO notice suspended activity in western Tehran FIR until Monday with limited airports operating sunrise-sunset (Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht, Ahvaz)\n\nThe key question: Does this evidence meet the standard of \"preponderance of the evidence\" that Iran initiated a major non-weather closure by May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET?\n\nLet's evaluate the rule requirements:\n- Iran initiated the closure: Evidence consistently shows Iranian Civil Aviation Authority (CAA)/Civil Aviation Organization as the issuing authority\n- Not solely weather-related: All reports indicate security/military context (US missile threats, etc.), no weather references\n- By May 24 deadline: NOTAM effective May 22 20:46Z to May 25 08:30Z - May 25 08:30Z is after 11:59 PM ET on May 24? Need to convert timezones.\n\nWait - we need to know if the closure was active at the deadline. May 25 08:30Z is 01:30 AM ET on May 25 (since Z is UTC, ET is UTC-5, so UTC 08:30 is ET 03:30). But May 24 11:59 PM ET is equivalent to May 25 04:59 UTC (which is less than 08:30 UTC), so the closure was active through the deadline.\n\n- \"Major closure\" definition: The rule has two paths:\n  1. Broad closure of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian airspace region\n  2. Complete suspension of commercial arrivals and departures affecting at least two listed airports\n\nFor path 1: Western Tehran FIR is a major Iranian airspace region? Yes, the rule defines this specifically - western airspace closure was mentioned as a qualifying example in PX-0.\n\nFor path 2: The rule requires complete suspension of commercial arrivals/departures at two listed airports. According to the evidence:\n- PX-1 says \"only eight airports across the country remain operational, including Tehran's Mehrabad and Imam Khomeini International, alongside Isfahan, Shiraz, Yazd, Tabriz, Mashhad and Bandar Abbas\"\n- DX-1 says \"several airports, including Urmia, Kerman, Abadan, Shiraz, Yazd, Kermanshah, Rasht and Ahvaz, were exempt from the restrictions but could operate only from sunrise to sunset\"\n\nFor path 2 to work, we'd need complete suspension at two of the listed airports (IKA, THR, MHD, SYZ, IFN). But PX-1 specifically lists Imam Khomeini International Airport (IKA) and Mehrabad Airport (THR) as operational with restrictions, meaning they're not completely suspended.\n\nRegarding DX-1: It claims the CAO \"denied issuing a new official aviation notice\" but also states \"activity at airports in the western part of Iran's flight information region, known as the Tehran FIR, had been suspended until Monday, with only a limited number of airports allowed to operate\". So they are acknowledging an earlier notice (not \"new\"), but it's still a CAO/CAA notice.\n\nThe core issue is whether this qualifies as a \"major closure\" under the rule:\n- The rule says \"a broad closure, cancellation, or suspension of commercial flights transiting, arriving in, and departing from Iranian airspace or a major Iranian Airspace region\"\n- The western Tehran FIR definitely qualifies as a major Iranian airspace region\n- The closure affected all airports in western Tehran FIR except limited daylight operations with fresh approval\n- The rule says \"limited exceptions to a broad closure, however, will not disqualify such a closure from counting\"\n\nThe plaintiff's position: The closure of western Tehran FIR (a major region) with limited exceptions meets the definition of \"major closure\" under the rule.\n\nThe defense's position: The evidence remains too ambiguous and lacks official NOTAM documentation to prove the specifics of the closure.\n\nThe rules for this case specify: \"The primary resolution sources for this market will be official information from Iranian aviation authorities and a consensus of credible reporting.\"\n\nThis is where the tension lies - plaintiff provides secondary reporting from multiple credible sources that all agree on the core details, while DX-1 is contradictory on some aspects but also confirms the western FIR closure. The defense wants the official NOTAM document, but the rule doesn't explicitly say the official document is required - it says \"primary resolution sources\" which can include \"a consensus of credible reporting.\"\n\nLooking at the evidence consistency:\n- All three plaintiff exhibits (PX-1, PX-2, PX-3) identify OIIX A1010/26 NOTAM for western Tehran FIR closure from May 22-25\n- All three mention the limited daylight operations with new approvals needed\n- PX-2 provides precise UTC timing, confirming the closure was in effect through May 24 deadline\n- DX-1 confirms the CAO/CAA has acknowledged a western FIR suspension with limited operations\n\nThe only discrepancy is whether there was a \"new\" notice - DX-1 says there wasn't a new notice, but PX-1-3 discuss the NOTAM OIIX A1010/26, which may have been issued before the denial statement, so there may not be a contradiction.\n\nBased on this, I believe the preponderance of evidence does show that Iran initiated a major closure meeting the market rule's definition. The plaintiff has identified multiple consistent secondary reports that converge on the same core facts, and even the defense's evidence (DX-1) partially corroborates the closure's existence while disputing the \"new\" nature of the notice.\n\nThe evidence shows:\n- Iran's civil aviation authority issued instructions for western Tehran FIR closure\n- It was effective before the deadline (May 24, 2026, 11:59 PM ET)\n- It was not weather-related (security context)\n- Western Tehran FIR qualifies as a major Iranian airspace region under the market rule\n- The rule specifically states that limited exceptions don't disqualify such a closure\n\nTherefore, the proposition should be \"demonstrated.\"\n\nBut let's be precise about what \"demonstrated\" means - it means the evidence shows the proposition is more likely true than not. There are reasonable doubts, but based on the consistent evidence from multiple sources and even the defense's own admission of some closure, I believe the preponderance standard is met.\n\nI should make sure I use the exact tool call format: `mcp` with tool `aar_submit_council_vote` and arguments as JSON string.\n\nThe rationale needs to be very brief - no more than 3 sentences.\n\nLet me draft a rationale:\n\"The admitted evidence from multiple credible sources consistently shows Iran's civil aviation authority imposed a western Tehran FIR closure with limited exceptions, effective before the deadline, for security reasons. The record confirms this qualifies as a major closure of a major Iranian airspace region under the rule, which permits limited exceptions. The preponderance of evidence supports the proposition.\"","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_a0f146d433d54ca58e91a1","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"Multiple consistent secondary reports confirm an Iranian civil aviation authority-imposed western Tehran FIR closure before the deadline for security reasons. The western FIR qualifies as a major airspace region under the rule, which allows limited exceptions. The"},"partialArgs":"{\"tool\": \"aar_submit_council_vote\", \"args\": \"{\\\"vote\\\":\\\"demonstrated\\\",\\\"rationale\\\":\\\"Multiple consistent secondary reports confirm an Iranian civil aviation authority-imposed western Tehran FIR closure before the deadline for security reasons. The western FIR qualifies as a major airspace region under the rule, which allows limited exceptions. The","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782834277031,"responseId":"gen-1782834277-uVQ9NIdIVG2CR2W3aYTH","responseModel":"qwen/qwen3-next-80b-a3b-thinking-2509"}}
